 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9839792222111974`*^9, 
  3.9839792326555915`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"72659a8c-94ab-4a48-a7c3-\
46939f795b09"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The First Orbital", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.983980152192795*^9, 
  3.9839801591409354`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"556dd93a-da25-41e9-b72a-\
5bff22c034c5"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Hydrogen atoms are the simplest element on the periodic table, as well as \
the most plentiful element in the observable universe. Yet despite their \
ubiquity, a completed understanding of hydrogen atoms proved elusive to \
scientists. In this notebook, we plan to model the electron orbitals of \
hydrogen atoms and build up the functions that the Resource Function \
HydrogenWavefunction uses.\n\nWe start with the Bohr model and with the \
spherical harmonics to show what energy levels are. We can draw a Bohr model \
manually using Graphics objects and using the Bohr radius for the different \
energy levels, showing what ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " means. We can introduce the idea of positional uncertainty with \
Sin[Sqrt[x^2+y^2]]/Sqrt[x^2+y^2]\nHeisenberg uncertainty using sums of sine \
waves, explaining the fundamental conflict with frequency and position.\n1D, \
2D, and 3D Particle in a Box--2D particle in a box: DensityPlot of two \
different sinusoidal plots, (Sin[m Pi*x]*Sin[n Pi*y])^2.\n\nGeneral idea: \
explain aspects of wavefunctions, until eventually using HydrogenWavefunction."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9839801899921885`*^9, 3.9839802651800127`*^9}, {
  3.9839803283714275`*^9, 3.983980344768021*^9}, {3.98398039452159*^9, 
  3.983980462434703*^9}, {3.983980565235056*^9, 3.9839806244789267`*^9}, {
  3.9839808008296113`*^9, 3.983980826564846*^9}, {3.9839809655965147`*^9, 
  3.983981081835898*^9}, {3.9839811223098125`*^9, 3.98398113237395*^9}, {
  3.9839812971957073`*^9, 3.9839813418417263`*^9}, {3.983981410140482*^9, 
  3.983981415953307*^9}, {3.9839815150332623`*^9, 3.983981551358763*^9}, {
  3.983981603732794*^9, 3.9839816242002363`*^9}, {3.985379716908289*^9, 
  3.9853797597305975`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e3cb5d34-e41b-43e8-adee-\
abf007e176aa"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The Bohr Model", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9853798808863277`*^9, 
  3.9853798867401943`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"60a1c7b2-9a81-4b81-b2aa-\
3b90d1c7fb13"],

Cell["\<\
Niels Bohr developed a model of the atom that built off Rutherford\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s discovery of the atomic nucleus. While somewhat primitive \
by today\[CloseCurlyQuote]s standards and inaccurate in many ways, it was by \
far the best atomic model that had been suggested. His big breakthrough was \
the idea of quantized electron energy levels, or shells. He pictured \
electrons as orbiting the nucleus, like planets around a star, and much like \
planets, these electrons would have a fixed radius for a given energy level. \
These energy levels have a fixed energy differential between them, and for an \
electron to jump from one energy level to a higher one, it needs to absorb \
light of precisely the corresponding amount of energy. When the electrons \
drops back down to the initial energy level, it would emit a photon with that \
same amount of energy. The following graphic shows the first three electron \
shells at the predicted radii, shown in blue, orbiting the nucleus, shown in \
red. Note that the size of the nucleus is not to scale.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9853799116235275`*^9, 3.9853801477061863`*^9}, {
  3.9853802830031543`*^9, 3.985380322688833*^9}, {3.985380353017729*^9, 
  3.9853804284367037`*^9}, {3.9853832285698414`*^9, 3.9853832581525817`*^9}, {
  3.985383296897958*^9, 
  3.985383371547036*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"92c50b62-5220-4201-b629-\
912644273f15"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

